## Step 8 — Can the Claimed Results Be Achieved?

### Short Answer: **Partially, with significant work.**

| Claimed Result | Achievable? | Required Work |
|---|---|---|
| MAPE 8.3% | **Maybe.** Depends on dataset. For clean, weekly-seasonal retail data, Prophet + FFT + holidays can achieve 8-12% MAPE. For noisy MSME data, more likely 12-18%. | Implement proper temporal cross-validation. Run on Diwali/Supermarket datasets with walk-forward validation (not in-sample). |
| Cost reduction 23.7% over (s,S) | **Possible but smaller.** MCTS can beat static policies, but the margin depends heavily on demand distributions and cost ratios. 10-20% is more realistic. | Implement proper (s,S) and ROP baselines. Run 100+ trials with different seeds. Report confidence intervals. |
| Bullwhip 2.4→1.15 | **Current calculation methodology is invalid.** With proper order stream variance calculation, the improvement would likely be 15-30% (not 52%). | Fix the Bullwhip calculation: generate order streams from the MCTS policy, compute actual Var(orders)/Var(demand). |
| Service Level 94.2% | **Plausible with good MCTS tuning.** But currently not tracked. | Add service level tracking to the simulation. |
| Ablation results | **Can be achieved** with proper experimental infrastructure. | Build component toggles, run factorial experiments. |
| 1.4x DAG speedup | **Easily verifiable.** Measure sequential vs parallel time. | Add timing instrumentation. |

